    <p>1 So­cial dis­tanc­ing in Seoul</p>
    <p>Ques­tions have arisen about the ef­fec­tive­ness of so-called Level 2.5 so­cial dis­tanc­ing norms in Seoul, with experts crit­i­cis­ing “quar­an­tine holes” in the govern­ment’s lat­est pol­icy. The health au­thor­i­ties, how­ever, are wary of the eco­nomic and so­cial reper­cus­sions if so­cial dis­tanc­ing is raised to Level 3, the high­est level.</p>
    <p>• No gath­er­ings or meet­ings of more than 50 peo­ple in­doors, 100 out­doors.</p>
    <p>• No spec­ta­tors al­lowed for sports events.</p>
    <p>• On­line learn­ing for kinder­gartens and schools (ex­cept high school se­niors pre­par­ing for ex­ams in December).</p>
    <p>• Clo­sure of in­door pub­lic fa­cil­i­ties and 12 high-risk pri­vate fa­cil­i­ties in­clud­ing bars, karaoke clubs and In­ter­net cafes.</p>
    <p>• Telecom­mut­ing en­cour­aged for civil ser­vants and pri­vate com­pany work­ers.</p>
    <p>• On­line worship for churches. *Level 2 was im­posed in Seoul and greater Seoul on Aug 19, then ex­tended to the whole coun­try on Aug 23.</p>

